The fight over the streaming future of Sony=E2=80=99s long-running quiz sho=
w and
Wheel of Fortune represents a full-scale, high-stakes, and final deconstruc=
tion of a half-century of TV dealmaking, and an industry model that has bee=
n in decline for years.

Eriq Gardner ( https://puck.news/author/eriq-gardner/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I=
%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hea=
ring%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Eriq Gardner ( https://puck.news/author/eriq-gardner/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I=
%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hea=
ring%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

The streaming land grab just claimed two of the last great holdouts:
Jeopardy! and Wheel of Fortune. Sony Pictures Television is officially shop=
ping the digital rights to both game-show juggernauts, a seismic shift for =
a pair of broadcast syndication staples that, until now, had been precious =
relics of the linear era. =E2=80=9CThe world is changing around us,=E2=80=
=9D Sony=E2=80=99s television chairman, Keith Le Goy, told The New York Tim=
es.

=C2=A0

Ah, but
there=E2=80=99s more to the story. Sony worked hard to frame the move as un=
related to its nasty legal fight with CBS over syndication rights. But in r=
eality, this is all about the hundreds of millions of dollars these shows g=
enerate annually, as well as the broader shake-up at CBS=E2=80=99s parent c=
ompany, Paramount Global, which is in the process of being taken over by Da=
vid Ellison=E2=80=99s Skydance. Of course streaming would become a flashpoi=
nt: Sony=E2=80=99s decision to explore a
digital home for the twin towers of syndication=E2=80=94possibly with Netfl=
ix or Peacock=E2=80=94follows its attempt to terminate a 40-plus-year-old a=
greement, effectively reclaiming full control of the licensing for the show=
s, which each command about 7 million viewers every night. In short, this h=
as become a full-scale, high-stakes deconstruction of a half-century of TV =
dealmaking, a final battle over an industry model that, for better or worse=
, is dying.

=C2=A0

CBS has already fired a warning shot, I=E2=80=99ve learned, arguing that So=
ny=E2=80=99s attempt to shop streaming rights separately is a blatant breac=
h of contract. While Sony believes it can license next-day rights immediate=
ly and same-day rights starting in 2028, when Jeopardy! syndication deals w=
ith TV stations expire, CBS sees the situation as far murkier. In a Novembe=
r 26 letter from its Weil Gotshal legal team, CBS argued that Sony would ef=
fectively be
competing against its own partner, undermining CBS=E2=80=99s ability to max=
imize TV station licensing fees and ad revenue. The letter states: =E2=80=
=9CThe digital rights should be sold together, and Sony will be responsible=
 for any harm that results from any decision Sony makes to the contrary.=E2=
=80=9D

I hear that CBS is not backing down, and plans to take the issue to Los Ang=
eles Superior Court Judge Kevin Brazile, who issued a restraining order sev=
eral weeks ago meant to
preserve the status quo. Sony, for its part, will counter that none of this=
 should come as a surprise. The shift to streaming has been in the works fo=
r years, the studio will contend, with plenty of pitch meetings where the t=
opic was openly discussed. And of course, the 1980s-era syndication agreeme=
nts say nothing specifically about streaming. As is often the case in these=
 disputes=E2=80=94where both sides are fighting over contracts drafted in t=
he pre-digital world=E2=80=94the silence may or may not be
meaningful. Either way, expect to hear plenty more.

The Shari Distraction Theory
----------------------------

It=E2=80=99s worth remembering that Jeopardy! and Wheel of Fortune,
along with other iconic game and talk shows, owe much of their success to a=
 1970s decision by the F.C.C. to rein in the major networks=E2=80=99 strang=
lehold on content. The rule change cracked open the industry for independen=
t players, such as legendary talk show host Merv Griffin, who created Jeopa=
rdy! and Wheel of Fortune, and Roger King, who struck a deal with Griffin=
=E2=80=99s production company to exclusively syndicate both shows. King
built King World, a distribution empire that also included The Oprah Winfre=
y Show, Rachael Ray, and Inside Edition. King and his siblings were legenda=
ry schmoozers, personally selling Hollywood to station executives across th=
e country.

But nothing stays independent in Hollywood forever. By the late =E2=80=9990=
s, those so-called fin-syn rules had been mostly dismantled, paving the way=
 for media giants to swallow up syndication
businesses. In 1999, CBS bought King World for $2.5 billion in stock, just =
as the studios were hoarding networks and distribution arms. Meanwhile, Mer=
v Griffin Enterprises eventually landed with Sony=E2=80=94after a brief and=
 bizarre stopover at Coca-Cola. (Yes, Coca-Cola once owned Jeopardy!=E2=80=
=94give me =E2=80=9Cweird corporate detours=E2=80=9D for $1,000.)

That=E2=80=99s why Sony and CBS find themselves in court over a distributio=
n deal that neither company directly
signed. But the bigger question is why now=E2=80=94and that=E2=80=99s where=
 things get stormy. Sony, of course, has become an arms dealer=E2=80=94the =
one Hollywood major without a general-interest streaming platform of its ow=
n=E2=80=94so it lives and dies by licensing. CBS, on the other hand, contro=
ls the syndication pipeline for Jeopardy! and Wheel, which makes the Sony p=
lay here look like a power grab. According to CBS, Sony made a nine-figure =
buyout offer early last year, and when that didn=E2=80=99t
work, it started pointing to =E2=80=9Cgarden-variety=E2=80=9D accounting vi=
olations as an excuse to blow up the old deal.

Sony doesn=E2=80=99t see those violations as minor. The company claims that=
 the Shari Redstone=E2=80=93era cost cuts at Paramount have left CBS=E2=80=
=99s syndication business weakened, with fewer resources to market the show=
s and secure top-tier licensing and ad dollars. Sony is also unhappy that C=
BS let its Nielsen ratings deal
lapse (it recently re-signed), and says it had to step in to help Jeopardy!=
 land continued Procter & Gamble advertisements.

Then there=E2=80=99s the question of whether CBS has been using these cash =
cows illicitly to prop up the rest of its syndication slate. Sony alleges t=
hat Jeopardy! and Wheel of Fortune are being bundled with far-less-popular =
shows that CBS wholly owns, like Hot Bench and The Drew Barrymore
Show, diverting revenue. Sony is also accusing CBS of selling the game show=
s to its own stations at below-market rates, in breach of an obligation to =
secure maximum receipts. In short, Sony sees CBS as coasting on the past.

Notably, this dispute is unfolding just as the Skydance-Paramount merger si=
ts before the F.C.C., which must approve the transfer of CBS=E2=80=99s broa=
dcast licenses. While the government=E2=80=99s review doesn=E2=80=99t direc=
tly involve CBS
Media Ventures=E2=80=94its syndication arm=E2=80=94there have been calls fo=
r the F.C.C. to impose fin-syn-style conditions on the deal. Sony is arguin=
g that the merger could cost jobs and further erode CBS=E2=80=99s ability t=
o distribute Jeopardy! and Wheel, giving Sony all the more reason to take c=
ontrol itself.

Is there even more going on? I=E2=80=99ve also heard the theory that Sony i=
s taking advantage of Paramount=E2=80=99s regulatory distractions=E2=80=94s=
trategically timing this push
while the company=E2=80=99s incoming and outgoing leaders have their hands =
full with the merger. Last year, Sony tapped Jill Ratner as its new general=
 counsel, bringing the aggressive attorney over from Disney. And in this ca=
se, the involvement of Marc Seltzer and Davida Brook at Susman Godfrey=E2=
=80=94big names in the legal community, but hardly entertainment specialist=
s=E2=80=94has raised eyebrows. Perhaps Sony decided this was the perfect mo=
ment to test whether CBS
was open to renegotiating legacy agreements that make little sense now that=
 the clubby syndication era is just about over, and the economics of televi=
sion have shifted.

The Restraining Order
---------------------

This fight could be nothing short of existential for CBS=E2=80=99s syndicat=
ion
division=E2=80=94once a crown jewel of the Redstone empire with Oprah, Judg=
e Judy, and everyone=E2=80=99s favorite early evening game shows. In declar=
ations that CBS submitted in support of its request for the restraining ord=
er, Scott Trupchak, a top CBS advertising executive, said that Sony=E2=80=
=99s attempted takeover of distribution has rattled clients and agencies, l=
eading them to question CBS=E2=80=99s ability to fulfill its commitments. G=
reg Guenther, a senior vice
president, said licensees are now doubting CBS=E2=80=99s authority=E2=80=94=
one network, the BBC, has even asked for indemnification. Angela Kucharski,=
 a CBS marketing executive, said the lawsuit has thrown the company=E2=80=
=99s credibility into question and created chaos among station groups like =
Sinclair Broadcast Group, which owns hundreds of Fox and ABC affiliates acr=
oss the country.

=C2=A0

It was this kind of
industry-wide panic=E2=80=94plus the possibility of triggering hundreds of =
secondary lawsuits from CBS=E2=80=99s partners=E2=80=94that prompted Judge =
Brazile to step in last month. After Sony started telling the industry that=
 it had officially terminated CBS=E2=80=99s rights to Jeopardy! and Wheel o=
f Fortune=E2=80=94and that stations and advertisers should now deal directl=
y with Sony=E2=80=94Brazile ordered the parties to hit pause.

=C2=A0

For
a moment, it seemed possible that the uncertainty might yank the game shows=
 off the air entirely. That didn=E2=80=99t happen, but Brazile=E2=80=99s or=
der was a recognition of the enormity of the stakes. Now, with a more lasti=
ng injunction request in front of him, he has to decide who=E2=80=99s likel=
y to prevail=E2=80=94and whether outright termination of a decades-old agre=
ement is really the appropriate remedy for whatever problems have come up.

It=E2=80=99s worth asking why anyone would want to
own CBS right now. Between the inevitable legal showdowns over digital righ=
ts, and the ongoing headaches with 60 Minutes and Trump=E2=80=99s election =
interference lawsuit, Bill Paley=E2=80=99s once-storied Tiffany Network is =
challenged. I hear Skydance is watching all of this closely=E2=80=94but the=
y=E2=80=99re not walking away.

=E2=80=8A

