alt:
28.799999999999997px;"><strong>The Shari Distraction Theory</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">It=E2=80=99s worth remembering that <em>Jeopardy!</em> and <=
em>Wheel of Fortune</em>,
along with other iconic game and talk shows, owe much of their success to a=
 1970s decision by the F.C.C. to rein in the major networks=E2=80=99 strang=
lehold on content. The rule change cracked open the industry for independen=
t players, such as legendary talk show host <strong>Merv Griffin</strong>, =
who created <em>Jeopardy!</em> and <em>Wheel of Fortune</em>, and <strong>R=
oger</strong> <strong>King</strong>, who struck a deal with Griffin=E2=80=
=99s production company to exclusively syndicate both shows. King
built King World, a distribution empire that also included <em>The Oprah Wi=
nfrey Show</em>, <em>Rachael Ray</em>, and <em>Inside Edition</em>. King an=
d his siblings were legendary schmoozers, personally selling Hollywood to s=
tation executives across the country.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;"><br/>But nothing stays independent in Hollywood forever. By the late=
 =E2=80=9990s, those so-called fin-syn rules had been mostly dismantled, pa=
ving the way for media giants to swallow up syndication
businesses. In 1999, CBS bought King World for $2.5 billion in stock, just =
as the studios were hoarding networks and distribution arms. Meanwhile, Mer=
v Griffin Enterprises eventually landed with Sony=E2=80=94after a brief and=
 bizarre stopover at Coca-Cola. (Yes, Coca-Cola once owned <em>Jeopardy!</e=
m>=E2=80=94give me =E2=80=9Cweird corporate detours=E2=80=9D for $1,000.)<b=
r/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">That=E2=80=99s why Son=
y and CBS find themselves in court over a distribution deal that neither co=
mpany directly
signed. But the bigger question is why<em> now</em>=E2=80=94and that=E2=80=
=99s where things get stormy. Sony, of course, has become an arms dealer=E2=
=80=94the one Hollywood major without a general-interest streaming platform=
 of its own=E2=80=94so it lives and dies by licensing. CBS, on the other ha=
nd, controls the syndication pipeline for <em>Jeopardy!</em> and <em>Wheel<=
/em>, which makes the Sony play here look like a power grab. According to C=
BS, Sony made a nine-figure buyout offer early last year, and when that did=
n=E2=80=99t
work, it started pointing to =E2=80=9Cgarden-variety=E2=80=9D accounting vi=
olations as an excuse to blow up the old deal.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Sony doesn=E2=80=99t see those violations as mino=
r. The company claims that the <strong>Shari</strong> <strong>Redstone</str=
ong>=E2=80=93era cost cuts at Paramount have left CBS=E2=80=99s syndication=
 business weakened, with fewer resources to market the shows and secure top=
-tier licensing and ad dollars. Sony is also unhappy that CBS let its Niels=
en ratings deal
lapse (it recently re-signed), and says it had to step in to help <em>Jeopa=
rdy!</em> land continued Procter &amp; Gamble advertisements.<br/><br/></p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Then there=E2=80=99s the question =
of whether CBS has been using these cash cows illicitly to prop up the rest=
 of its syndication slate. Sony alleges that <em>Jeopardy!</em> and <em>Whe=
el of Fortune</em> are being bundled with far-less-popular shows that CBS w=
holly owns, like <em>Hot Bench</em> and <em>The Drew Barrymore
Show</em>, diverting revenue. Sony is also accusing CBS of selling the game=
 shows to its own stations at below-market rates, in breach of an obligatio=
n to secure maximum receipts. In short, Sony sees CBS as coasting on the pa=
st.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Notably, this dis=
pute is unfolding just as the Skydance-Paramount merger sits before the F.C=
=2EC., which must approve the transf=
er of CBS=E2=80=99s broadcast licenses. W=
hile the government=E2=80=99s review doesn=E2=80=99t directly involve CBS
Media Ventures=E2=80=94its syndication arm=E2=80=94there have been calls fo=
r the F.C.C. to impose fin-syn-style conditions on the deal. Sony is arguin=
g that the merger could cost jobs and further erode CBS=E2=80=99s ability t=
o distribute <em>Jeopardy!</em> and <em>Wheel</em>, giving Sony all the mor=
e reason to take control itself.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Is the=
re even more going on? I=E2=80=99ve also heard the theory that Sony is taki=
ng advantage of Paramount=E2=80=99s regulatory distractions=E2=80=94strateg=
ically timing this push
while the company=E2=80=99s incoming and outgoing leaders have their hands =
full with the merger. Last year, Sony tapped <strong>Jill Ratner</strong> a=
s its new general counsel, bringing the aggressive attorney over from Disne=
y. And in this case, the involvement of <strong>Marc Seltzer</strong> and <=
strong>Davida Brook</strong> at Susman Godfrey=E2=80=94big names in the leg=
al community, but hardly entertainment specialists=E2=80=94has raised eyebr=
ows. Perhaps Sony decided this was the perfect moment to test whether CBS
was open to renegotiating legacy agreements that make little sense now that=
 the clubby syndication era is just about over, and the economics of televi=
sion have shifted.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
