28.799999999999997px;"><strong>The Restraining Order</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">This fight could be nothing short of existential for CBS=E2=
=80=99s syndication
division=E2=80=94once a crown jewel of the Redstone empire with <em>Oprah</=
em>, <em>Judge Judy</em>, and everyone=E2=80=99s favorite early evening gam=
e shows. In declarations that CBS submitted in support of its request for t=
he restraining order, <strong>Scott Trupchak</strong>, a top CBS advertisin=
g executive, said that Sony=E2=80=99s attempted takeover of distribution ha=
s rattled clients and agencies, leading them to question CBS=E2=80=99s abil=
ity to fulfill its commitments. <strong>Greg Guenther</strong>, a senior vi=
ce
president, said licensees are now doubting CBS=E2=80=99s authority=E2=80=94=
one network, the BBC, has even asked for indemnification. <strong>Angela Ku=
charski</strong>, a CBS marketing executive, said the lawsuit has thrown th=
e company=E2=80=99s credibility into question and created chaos among stati=
on groups like Sinclair Broadcast Group, which owns hundreds of Fox and ABC=
 affiliates across the country.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">It was this kind of
industry-wide panic=E2=80=94plus the possibility of triggering hundreds of =
secondary lawsuits from CBS=E2=80=99s partners=E2=80=94that prompted Judge =
Brazile to step in last month. After Sony started telling the industry that=
 it had officially terminated CBS=E2=80=99s rights to <em>Jeopardy!</em> an=
d <em>Wheel of Fortune</em>=E2=80=94and that stations and advertisers shoul=
d now deal directly with Sony=E2=80=94Brazile ordered the parties to hit pa=
use.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">For
a moment, it seemed possible that the uncertainty might yank the game shows=
 off the air entirely. That didn=E2=80=99t happen, but Brazile=E2=80=99s or=
der was a recognition of the enormity of the stakes. Now, with a more lasti=
ng injunction request in front of him, he has to decide who=E2=80=99s likel=
y to prevail=E2=80=94and whether outright termination of a decades-old agre=
ement is really the appropriate remedy for whatever problems have come up.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>It=E2=80=99s worth asking why <em>anyone</em=
> would want to
own CBS right now. Between the inevitable legal showdowns over digital righ=
ts, and the ongoing headaches with <em>60 Minutes</em> and Trump=E2=80=99s =
election interference lawsuit, <strong>Bill Paley</strong>=E2=80=99s once-s=
toried Tiffany Network is challenged. I hear Skydance is watching all of th=
is closely=E2=80=94but they=E2=80=99re not walking away.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
